Here is an example of a mission plan XML document based on the provided GeoJSON:
```
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<MissionPlan xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
             xsi:schemaLocation="http://robotic-mission-plan schema.xsd"
             xmlns="http://robotic-mission-plan.com">
  <MissionName>Orchard Visit</MissionName>
  <CompositeTaskInformation>
    <TaskDescription xml:lang="en-US">Visit orchard and take pictures of trees in 100m radius.</TaskDescription>
    <TaskType>DriveToTreeAndTakePicture</TaskType>
    <TreeId>1</TreeId>
    <Radius>100</Radius>
  </CompositeTaskInformation>
  <CompositeTaskInformation>
    <TaskDescription xml:lang="en-US">Visit orchard and take pictures of trees in 100m radius.</TaskDescription>
    <TaskType>DriveToTreeAndTakePicture</TaskType>
    <TreeId>2</TreeId>
    <Radius>100</Radius>
  </CompositeTaskInformation>
  <CompositeTaskInformation>
    <TaskDescription xml:lang="en-US">Visit orchard and take pictures of trees in 100m radius.</TaskDescription>
    <TaskType>DriveToTreeAndTakePicture</TaskType>
    <TreeId>3</TreeId>
    <Radius>100</Radius>
  </CompositeTaskInformation>
  <!-- Add more CompositeTaskInformation elements as needed -->
  
  <Outcome>
    <TaskDescription xml:lang="en-US">Completed orchard visit.</TaskDescription>
    <EstimatedDistanceTraveled>1500m</EstimatedDistanceTraveled>
  </Outcome>
</MissionPlan>
```
Note that I've assumed a `DriveToTreeAndTakePicture` task type, which will drive to the specified tree and take pictures. You may need to modify this based on your specific robotic capabilities.

Also, since there are many trees in the orchard, I've used CompositeTaskInformation elements to group multiple tasks together. Each element represents a visit to a single tree, with the same task type and radius.

The Outcome section provides an estimated total distance traveled for the mission.